hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a rare Mendelian disorder modeled by a recessive–recessive complementary digenic inheritance at two unlinked autosomal loci, denoted by locus $A$ with alleles $A$ and $a$, and locus $B$ with alleles $B$ and $b$. Affected status is encoded by a binary phenotype indicator $Y$, where $Y=1$ denotes affected and $Y=0$ denotes unaffected. The genotype-to-phenotype mapping (penetrance) is defined by
$$
P(Y=1 \mid \text{genotype}) = 
\begin{cases}
1  \text{if the genotype is } aa\,bb, \\
0  \text{for all other genotypes.}
\end{cases}
$$
Assume both parents are known to be heterozygous at both loci, specifically each parent has genotype $Aa\,Bb$. Assume the loci are unlinked, meiosis follows Mendel’s law of segregation and the law of independent assortment, there is no segregation distortion, and sibling genotypes are independent conditional on parental genotypes.

Using only the foundational principles of Mendel’s laws and the definition of penetrance given above, compute the recurrence risk to siblings of an affected proband, that is, the probability that a subsequent sibling born to these same $Aa\,Bb$ parents is affected. Express your final answer as a reduced fraction. No rounding is required, and no units are applicable.
